 Description:
 [P40A / DC020 DUAL BAND RADAR (DBR)]: Funding is required to maintain the In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) and Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) production services and support for
 Configuration Management. Funding also implements the DBR Life Cycle Sustainment Plan (LCSP) and infrastructure, Diminishing Manufacturing Sources and Material Shortages (DMSMS) Plan, associated
 hardware and software obsolescence mod kits, procurement of Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs), associated logistics products and on-board repair parts allowance requirements to enable system
 operation. Additionally, funding is required for a technology refresh for the DBR Signal Data Processors (SDPs) for CVN 78 and DDG 1000 Class ships. The current version of the IBM Advanced Interactive
 eXecutive (AIX) operating system (OS) that is running on the IBM P6 DBR SDPs reached the end of service in FY22 and the risk for DBR to satisfy Cyber Authority to Operate (ATO) requirements will increase.
 The next version of IBM AIX OS will not run on the IBM P6. Hardware spares for DBR SDP P6 computers are no longer available from IBM or certified IBM vendors. Production Support is also required to
 assist with DBR Combat System Integration and Technical Documentation. Funding also supports CVN 78 and DDG 1000 Class Operational Testing (OT) events. Additional limitations will be identified during
 DDG 1001 Shipboard Activation, as well as the CVN 78 and DDG 1000 deployments. The OEM and Government Technical Team have documented the critical radar issues that require correction via ECPs.
 Funding for these ECP efforts is required due to the engineering and technical complexity of the change proposals needed to satisfy combat system qualification requirements. The four DBR systems on CVN
 78 and the three DDG 1000 class ships will be the full extent of the population. The small inventory of DBR based radars are also out of production and therefore, require increasing investments in obsolescence
 engineering, OEM repairs, and continuous onboard OEM technical support in order to maintain an acceptable level of operational availability. The DBR program received additional sustainment resources in
 FY26 to maintain the systems until the Navy decides to replace them with a more sustainable alternative. DBR Special Test Equipment and Infrastructure funding is needed for: (1) test equipment and support for
 a repair depot for assemblies and subassemblies for DBR components, including Common Array Power System (CAPS), and Common Array Cooling System (CACS); (2) resolution of system obsolescence that
 will degrade system Ao; and (3) establishment of product support engineering infrastructure needed by the DBR In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) and OEM onboard technicians to test and resolve issues for
 deployed systems on DDG 1000 Class and CVN 78. The additional DBR sustainment and infrastructure efforts will facilitate the transition of material sparing support of DBR to NAVSUP.

 [P40A / DC022 RADAR RESTORATION MATERIAL]: Radar Restoration funding across the FYDP procures mandatory replacement material in support of radar restoration such as arrays, overhaul kits (various
 components including waveguides, nuts, bolts, bearings, washers, seals, etc.), miscellaneous antenna sub-assemblies, and Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs) to address obsolescence and improve
 supportability. FY26 to FY27 decrease is due to funding reductions to support higher Navy requirements.

 [P40A / DC026 I-STALKER]: Improved Stalker (I-Stalker) is the Independent Mount (IM) Improvement to the Stalker Long Range Electro-Optic Sensor System (SLREOSS) system fielded in response to a 2016
 United States Fleet Forces Command (USFFC) Operational Needs Statement (ONS). I-Stalker is currently fielded on CVN and LHA/LHD ship classes and is planned for installation on the first 10 Constellation
 Class FFGs. I-Stalker provides for 360-degree situational awareness and enhances ships to passively detect, classify, identify, and determine intent of current/emerging surface and air threats in support of the
 following warfare missions: Surface/Air Recon, Counter-Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS), Counter-Fast Attack Craft/Fast Inshore Attack Craft (FAC/FIAC), Search & Rescue, Force Protection, and Mobility.


