 Description:
 The Cryptologic Carry-On-Program (CCOP) procures state-of-the-art, commercial off-the-shelf Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) equipment (hardware and software) in response to combatant commander
 requirements for a quick-reaction surface, subsurface, and airborne cryptologic carry-on capability. The equipment is procured in accordance with requirements detailed in the shipboard Information Warfare /
 Cryptologic System Operational Requirements Document and specific execution year fleet requirements. These requirements are defined by Fleet Cyber Command (FCC)/Commander TENTH Fleet (C10F) Fleet
 Signals Development Working Group (FSDWG), in concert with Shipboard Signals Exploitation Space (SSES) programs (includes Ship's Signal Exploitation Equipment Family of Systems) to ensure synergy and
 seamless transition to permanently installed systems. The FSDWG meets to determine which signals of interest (SOI)s/Targets on the FSDWG list need to be addressed. Due to a continually changing threat
 environment, detailed requirements are dynamic and equipment procured varies each year by quantity and type. Equipment suites can be configured for many targets and tasking. Target specific subsystems
 can either operate as stand-alone within the cryptologic spaces or as an add-on to existing equipment. Hardware procurements includes: receivers, recorders, tactical computers and related peripherals,
 antennas, electronic-warfare support measures systems, precision geolocation equipment, advanced signal and search equipment including spectrum analyzers and associated portable special intelligence
 communications equipment. CCOP equipment is installed as an augment to cryptologic capabilities on subsurface, surface, and air platforms. There are approximately 124 cryptologic capable surface ships
 and shore sites in the current Navy inventory. Each of these are potential users of this carry-on equipment, as are subsurface and air platforms. The temporary installation of equipment is coordinated through
 fleet augmentation requests and installed by fleet electronic support personnel. A primary system in inventory is the Carry On Radio Spectrum Analysis & Intelligence Reporting (CORSAIR) system. Funds
 continue to procure CORSAIR core architecture system upgrades to provide additional affordable functionality to the combatant commands. Additional signal acquisition equipment to address specific combatant
 command requirements include such systems as Digital Receiver Technology (DRT), Hostile forces Integrated Targeting Service (HITS), Maritime Toxic Pen (MTP), TURBULENTWAVE / TURBULENTWIND /
 TURBULENTSAIL / BLUESTREAM servers, RED FALCON, FIREFLY, NIMBLE TRACKER, SHEARWATER, CARBON STORM, XML to JREAP-C (X2J), TOXIC SMOKE, QUICKSHOT, SHOCKWAVE/WSTL,
 and Remote Analytical SIGINT Capability (RASCAL) equipment. Starting in FY 2026, CCOP consolidated into budget line item 2360 to group technology projects fostering innovation and efficiency.

 The U.S. Navy's Global Signals Analysis Laboratory (GSAL) program under project CLASSIC SENSEI provides technical management and resource allocation in support of worldwide Information Warfare (IW)
 operations. The GSAL program supports a global architecture of Signals Analysis Laboratories (SALs) distributed throughout the world in fleet centric and strategic Operating Areas (OPAREAs). The primary
 mission is to facilitate the National/Tactical Processing, Exploitation, and Dissemination (PED) of Technical Signals Intelligence (TechSIGINT) data collected within the maritime domain while simultaneously
 functioning as an extension of tactical assets forward deployed. The program's Mission, Functions, and Tasks (MF&T) are facilitated through the use of the RoNIN - Mission System. RoNIN represents a truly joint
 National/Tactical infrastructure solution that provides analysts throughout the Intelligence Community (IC) with direct and remote access to tactical mission payloads using both existing and cloud based analytical
 tools and resources. The GSAL program and the RoNIN - Mission System function as the backbone for U.S. Navy's worldwide TechSIGINT PED.




