INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0093$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$93$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 The level of sonobuoy procurement funding directly enables the Navy's overall Anti-submarine Warfare (ASW) mission and wartime readiness. The Air ASW program buys-to-budget based on actual fleet
 usage, fleet forecasted usage, and best negotiated pricing across all sonobuoy types. The Air ASW community continues to use passive capability combined with an increase in the more capable Multi-static
 Active Coherent (MAC) wide area search Concept of Operations (CONOPS), which uses the AN/SSQ-101 and AN/SSQ-125 family of systems. While the transition to MAC requires the procurement of more
 sophisticated sonobuoys, the resulting wide area search capability is more efficient and effective. The MAC capability provides the foundational Air ASW acoustic search capability for the P-8 Poseidon, and
 increasing the inventory of MAC sonobuoys is required to support the combatant commander's ASW mission execution requirements. This funding profile allows the Navy to prioritize and meet current operational
 forward presence requirements while building fleet commander deployment readiness levels in the ASW mission area.


 NOTES:
 1. FY 2027 reflects the almost complete industrial base transition from single source with ERAPSCO Joint Venture to a competitive environment where previous ERAPSCO partners (Sparton and Ultra-Undersea
 Sensor Systems, Inc (USSI)) will each produce fully independent designs. Sparton and USSI will compete annually for USG orders via a competitive multiple award delivery order contract (MADOC). In the event
 only one vendor is qualified, the USG will use sole source contracts as necessary as bridge efforts to full competition. Future unit costs are estimated using an Independent Government Cost Estimate (IGCE)
 derived from prior year proposals and contract awards, new vendor base establishment, sonobuoy re-qualification efforts, future production learning curves, supply chain changes, and splitting quantities across
 multiple vendors. USG independent cost estimate utilizes split awards in order to preserve the health of the industrial base. Actual split will be dependent on company proposals for each annual delivery order.
 Additionally, production engineering and lot acceptance costs have increased based on increased effort associated with testing product from multiple vendors. Increased funding levels also support product
 acceptance test infrastructure at various locations and may be used to procure strategic critical parts, material and tooling to enable industry base surge during wartime/contingency operations and mitigate
 supply chain risks. FY 2026/FY 2027 begin the inclusion of substantial cost increases associated with stand up of a new air-launch Contractor Owned, Contractor Operated capability for lot acceptance test efforts
 due to sundown of the P-3 aircraft, scheduling conflicts and lack of availability of aircraft required to complete lot acceptance test events for sonobuoy delivery. Funding also supports product acceptance test
 infrastructure at various locations and may be used to procure strategic critical parts, material and tooling to enable industry base surge during wartime/contingency operations and mitigate supply chain risks.

 2. Program buys-to-budget. New MADOC does not have maximum quantity limitations, maximizing industry capacity; ceiling is based on number of available vendors per buoy variant and price points based on
 quantity procured. Program seeks to achieve economies of scale by utilizing both Other Procurement Navy (OPN) and Foreign Military Sales (FMS) funds. Under the MADOC, production quantities will be split
 amongst qualified vendors for the health of the industrial base, reducing economic ordering quantities.

 3. FY 2027 will continue competition of the AN/SSQ-36 and AN/SSQ-53 across two vendors. Unit costs assumed a split between two vendors to ensure health/viability of the industrial base, leading to loss of
 economical ordering quantities, higher unit prices and data from the past two years of competitive actions. FY 2027 reflects the first opportunity for a competitive approach to AN/SSQ-62. It is planned to be
 single sourced through FY 2026 as vendors continued to qualify independent buoy designs. FY 2027 will continue as a single source contract for the AN/SSQ-125B. FY 2025 and FY 2026 quantity and unit cost
 adjustments were a result of extensive qualification costs, learning curve reset for independent buoy designs and independent production lines. Program deferred AN/SSQ-101 buoy order to FY 2026 to better
 align AN/SSQ-101 and AN/SSQ-125 inventory levels and avoid demil expenditures; FY 2027 AN/SSQ-101 order will utilize FY 2025, FY 2026 and FY 2027 funds to optimize procurement strategy and gain
 economies of scale. As a result of the various contracting strategies, FY 2027 projected unit costs do not reflect traditional cost trends.



