 Justification:
 This line funds TMPC and TTWCS system modernization upgrades.

 FY 2027 Tomahawk Weapons System funds provide for integration, modernization and interoperability efforts necessary to keep pace with changes and threats, retain capability and exploit capabilities of
 internal products (TWS All-Up-Round missile and TTWCS) and external products (Modernized Integrated Data Base (MIDB), National Geospatial Intelligence Agency (NGA) products, Distributed Common
 Ground Systems (DCGS) Integrated Backbone (DIB) compliance, Future Imagery Architecture (FIA) imagery formats and Intelligence Surveillance & Reconnaissance (ISR) interfaces, Network Centric Enterprise
 Services (NCES), and Global Information Grid. These efforts ensure the continued effectiveness and relevance of the Tomahawk Weapons System.

 TMPC: FY 2027 funding is required to continue the upgrade of unsupportable and obsolete TMPC hardware and software, ensure compliance with DoW cyber-security mandates, and continue fielding TMPC
 7.X. FY 2027 also funds upgrades necessary to improve cybersecurity posture across all TMPC sites to a minimum required level of robustness, resiliency, and cyber survivability in light of the constantly evolving
 technology and threat space to preserve national first-strike Tomahawk system of systems capability. These upgrades are required for development of TMPC 8.X, fielding TMPC 7.X, and support the employment
 and capability of the Joint Multiple Effects Munitions (JMEWS) and Maritime Strike Tomahawk (MST) programs. These upgrades enable fielding of advanced capabilities of the Tomahawk Modernization program
 with required program protection safeguards to protect Critical Program Information. The increase in funding in FY 2027 is for the modernization and integration of TMPC X. This new version of TMPC will be
 an upgraded and modernized version of the three major components of TMPC: TPS, TNT, and MDS. This effort will include modern software development and architecture implementation, increased system
 performance, integrated cyber protections, reduced mission planning times as well as other system improvements. TMPC X will also provide the warfighter with a modern software suite that will support the
 current TWS mission and will allow for a more rapid delivery of future TWS requirements. The system will include networking equipment to integrate with the naval data exchange for unified strike planning and
 execution system to provide all source multi-intelligence data at multiple levels of security to strike mission planners. TMPC will incorporate cross domain solution capabilities to include data exchange with the
 Next Generation Mission Planning System.

 TTWCS: FY 2027 funding is required to continue modernization to software configurability, software language, and Human Computer Interface activities which will provide added improvements to the TTWCS
 suite of software products. These improvements ensure an enhanced security design, provide a flexible and modern software system to meet Fleet cybersecurity needs, and support focused modernization
 activities going forward. FY 2027 funding is required to continue addressing specific security and supportability builds for current software builds, procurement, and assembly activities associated with
 contemporary hardware integration efforts to support Tomahawk missile capabilities. FY 2027 funding supports the continued fielding of updated hardware and software releases to Firing Units, and integrated
 logistics support. Other FY 2027 activities include HW procurement, installation planning, modernization activities, long-term planning of future software versions, and technical data packages. Product
 improvement resources are required to comply with commercial hardware and software supportability mandates, obsolescence, and information assurance requirements to maintain pace with modern computing
 architectures and evolving cyber threats. TTWCS relies on COTS hardware and software tools that require a stable and established upgrade path to meet cyber security mandates, address supply chain risk
 management, ensure continued vendor supportability, quality assurance, and ensure interoperability between COTS software applications, operating systems, and hardware processing nodes.




