INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0120$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$120$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 Expeditionary:
 The FY27 funding supports the Navy Expeditionary Forces by continuing the initial outfitting of Airfield Damage Repair equipment to achieve Initial Operating Capability (IOC). It also funds Pier Damage Repair
 (PDR) equipment sets necessary to meet IOC requirements. Additionally, this funding will provide essential equipment for the initial outfitting of the new NCHB-3, enabling it to fulfill its Required Operational
 Capabilities (ROC) in a Projected Operational Environment (POE), which includes rearming, refueling, and resupplying fleet assets.

 The increased investment in Construction and Maintenance Equipment for Expeditionary Forces includes $9.37 million for Earthmoving Equipment and $3.313 million for Material Handling Equipment. This
 investment addresses critical shortages in items listed on the units' Table of Allowance (TOA) and facilitates the necessary recapitalization of over-aged equipment.

 The Acquisition strategy for Expeditionary Construction equipment has changed to a Family of Buy approach balanced with Fleet priorities to meet the Navy Response Plan. The strategy goal is to procure a
 platform within a short range of time to minimize the number of configurations of each platform. This approach minimizes sailor training requirements, product support development costs, repair parts, among
 others.

 The emphasis is filling gaps for critical equipment requirements associated with the Navy Response Plan and on recapitalizing older equipment is vital for improving readiness. Without reliable equipment in
 the fleet, there is significant risk in meeting in-theater operational mission requirements and deadlines for building, repairing, and maintaining critical infrastructure, such as roads, runways, and undertaking
 demolition, excavation, and underground utility work.

 Public Works:
 EARTHMOVING EQUIPMENT (BSO 52): Public Works (PW): FY27 reflects a decrease of $3.61M of Construction Equipment (C&E). This funding line is required to support the strategic recapitalization of
 NAVFAC'S aging and degraded Shore fleet, which is essential to maintaining resilient mission-ready installations. Much of the existing fleet is aged and has outlived its expected lifecycle, leading to increasing
 reliability concerns and escalating maintenance costs. This degradation impacts our ability to execute critical infrastructure projects on schedule and sustain operational readiness across the shore installations.

 This funding enables the replacement of mission-critical equipment required for key PW functions, including airfield and roadway construction and repair, utility excavation, facility demolition and emergency
 response. These capabilities directly affect the warfighter readiness. Without dependable equipment, project delays and mission degradation become likely, posing risks to force deployment timelines and the
 sustainment of critical infrastructure. Recapitalization this fleet ensures PW remains agile, responsive and fully equipped to delivery safe, reliable, and timely support to naval shore installations and warfighter
 readiness.




