INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0125$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$125$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 Special Purpose Vehicles (BSO 52): Public Works (PW): FY27 reflects a decrease ($4.3M) in supports the acquisition and sustainment of specialized vehicles critical for shore-based power and water
 infrastructure operations and Naval Surface Warfare Center mission. These vehicles are critical to maintaining daily operational effectiveness and installation readiness. These assets perform essential functions
 such as power line maintenance, cargo transport, equipment haulage, emergency response and base infrastructure support. Their availability to sustain base operations, maintain infrastructure, and support
 mission requirements at shore installation.

 Additionally, the funding supports fielding a fleet of Special Purpose Vehicles for Naval Special Warfare with expeditionary tent camp equipment used to support troops operating and training in the field; prime
 movers' trucks to tow special operations craft; and large trucks for moving ammunition, weapons and cargo. This logistic support is critical to train SEAL and Special Boat Teams for deployment. In addition,
 the funding line supports Expeditionary priority mission capabilities Mobile Boat Hoist (MBH) higher priority actions and new phased approach for NCHB-3 E/S and addresses table of allowance procurement
 wholeness for IOC units of action due to high priority items for Navy Response Plan (NRP). The funding reduction limits the Navy's ability to replace aging and unserviceable vehicles, delays modernization
 efforts, and increase maintenance burdens on an already strained fleet. Ongoing shortfalls will limit the Navy's ability to maintain essential vehicle capabilities, which can disrupt base operations, strain logistics,
 and reduce the level of support available to fleet activities, putting operational readiness and personnel safety at risk.

 Combat Construction Support Equipment - Expeditionary: FY27 funding continues to support procurement of trailers, expeditionary facilities and fuel/water services. Funds support acquisition of expeditionary
 basing engineered capabilities to integrate joint standardization board (JSB) approved equipment to ensure interoperability, energy enhancements and commonality across the Navy and DoW. These materiel
 assets support core mission requirements and are essential to the readiness and battlefield effectiveness.

 Mobile Utilities Support Equipment (MUSE): FY27 funds will be used to recapitalize the MUSE generator and substation equipment. Current inventory and condition assessment of MUSE power generation
 assets rated 77% of generation capability. The assessment also rated a zero percent capability to support CONUS prime power missions. The major risk is long term limited availability of MUSE (total and EPA
 compliant) generation assets with continued increases in unsupported MUSE missions.

 Railway Equipment: $16.1M increase in FY27 funds the urgent replacement of mission-critical dilapidated railcars to prevent operational failure. This investment directly addresses the rapidly declining state of
 the Navy's railcar inventory, which is essential for maintaining ordnance loading operations. The current railcars, averaging 75 years old and 47 years beyond their useful life expectancy as defined by NAVFAC
 P-300, are consistently failing and being removed from service, creating an increasingly fragile logistics capability.

 Ocean Construction Equipment: FY27 funds provided for procurement of specialized ocean construction equipment and will be utilized to procure underwater survey systems, underwater sonar systems, and
 underwater construction equipment.

 Special Purpose Vehicles (BSO 41): FY27 funds provided for procurement of various non-tactical special purpose vehicles, equipment, and trailers.

 Special Purpose Vehicles (BSO 30): FY27 funds provided for the procurement of BEARCATs to support mission requirements and replace existing vehicles used in security patrols and missile movement
 convoys; replacement is based on meeting or exceeded service life due to age and usage.

