INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0126$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$126$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6.732, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1.297, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 The 2027 budget request is mission-critical for the procurement of physical security vehicles including armored sedans and armored cargo/utility trucks used to support Antiterrorism (AT), Counterintelligence (CI),
 and Counternarcotics (CN) missions in high threat OCONUS environments. These platforms, categorized as Commercial Heavy Armored Vehicles (CHAVs) and Commercial Light Armored Vehicles (CLAVs), are
 configured with varying protection levels, survivability features, and mission-specific equipment based on threat conditions and operational requirements.

 These vehicles enable secure movement of personnel, classified materials, and sensitive equipment; support surveillance and interdiction operations; and provide protected mobility for forces conditioning AT/
 CI/CN activities. As threats evolve, the ability to field vehicles with appropriate ballistic protection, blast resistance, and mobility performance becomes increasingly essential. Aging or under-protected vehicles
 elevate operational risk, reduce mission flexibility, and increase vulnerability to surveillance, interdiction, and attack.

 Deferred replacement compounds risk by increasing maintenance downtime, reducing fleet availability, and degrading the ability of security forces to respond rapidly to emerging threats. In high-threat OCONUS
 environments, where host-nations support may be limited and U.S. Forces rely heavily on organic mobility, these gaps directly affect force protection posture and the safety of Navy personnel.




