INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0127$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$127$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 The FY27 budget request of $67.8 million for Supply Equipment represents a restoration of funding to the required operational baseline and includes the strategic realignment of NAVSUP's centralized
 procurement responsibilities. The significant variance from the FY26 enacted budget of $0 is the result of a one-time congressional decision that eliminated funding for that fiscal year.

 The FY27 request is driven by two primary factors:
 Centralization of Material Handling Equipment (MHE) Procurement ($63.1M): In alignment with OPNAVINST 4460.1C, NAVSUP is now the single point of accountability for all Navy MHE. This funding represents
 a transfer of responsibility from other commands to NAVSUP to address systemic equipment deficiencies through a unified, centrally managed strategy.

 Restoration of Critical Support Programs ($4.7M): This restores funding for essential programs, including the Navy Cash and Ordnance Information Systems (OIS) programs, which were forced to suspend
 operations and modernization efforts in FY26.

 This request is not growth, but funding restoration to address critical Fleet needs.

 NAVSUP's FY26 budget procurement line was erroneously eliminated due to misplaced congressional add for At-Sea Rearm of Vertical Launch System (T2). This eliminated all funding for MHE procurement,
 the Navy Cash program, and OIS. Consequently, all program activities including new procurements, system modernization, and technology refreshes were curtailed, creating significant operational and
 modernization gaps.

 Failure to fund this request in FY27 will have a two-fold negative impact:
 1. MHE Degradation: The Navy's strategic effort to correct systemic MHE deficiencies through centralized management will fail. Individual commands will be forced to continue funding MHE in an uncoordinated
 and inefficient manner, perpetuating existing readiness gaps.
 2. Capability Gaps: Critical support programs will be further degraded. The OIS tech refresh will be delayed, increasing risk in ordnance management. The Navy Cash program will be unable to support new
 deployments or modernization, negatively impacting sailor quality of life and financial accountability.




