 Description:
 The Ammunition Modernization budget is a critical investment in technical expertise that directly ensures the lethality, safety, and reliability of the ammunition our Marines carry into battle. This funding is essential
 for maintaining a decisive edge over our adversaries and safeguarding our warfighters. It funds the expert engineering and scientific analysis from Naval Surface Warfare Centers (NSWCs) required to support
 ammunition procurements, quality assurance in production and field the next generation of advanced ammunition. The program's rigorous testing, evaluation, and malfunction investigations identify and mitigate
 ammunition risks before they can endanger Marines. By analyzing and managing the service life of the entire ammunition stockpile, this ensures every round is safe and effective.

 The INTERNAL SUPPORT budget element is the command-and-control framework that enables the effective leadership and expert oversight of the entire Marine Corps ammunition enterprise. This funding is
 indispensable for guaranteeing the safety, security, and readiness of our multi-billion-dollar ammunition stockpile. This is not administrative support; it is the core operational capability that allows the Ammunition
 Life Cycle Management program office to do the following:
 Ensure fiscal integrity: Execute professional financial management to ensure the scrupulous, transparent, and accountable use of every dollar appropriated for the USMC's ammunition, a critical national security
 asset.
 Defend Against Cyber Threats: Provide the dedicated cybersecurity expertise required to protect the sensitive technical data, logistics information, and inventory of our entire stockpile from adversary espionage
 and disruption. Execute On-Site Technical Oversight: Fund the essential travel for program managers and technical experts to conduct hands-on quality assurance, witness testing, and perform critical safety
 inspections at depots, proving grounds, and manufacturing plants.

 The EXTERNAL SUPPORT budget is the critical funding line that allows the Marine Corps to utilize technical expertise of the Department of War's premier engineering and scientific centers of excellence for
 ammunition: Naval Surface Warfare Centers (NSWC) Crane, Dahlgren, and Indian Head. This is the sole funding line that allows the Marine Corps to leverage the specialized talent and infrastructure of these
 institutions to ensure the ammunition stockpile is safe, reliable and lethal. This funding line supports the following: Provides the core engineering and technical support required to procure and manage Marine
 Corps-unique or specialized ammunition items that fall outside what is available from the Single Manager for Conventional Ammunition. Funds the expert configuration management of Technical Data Packages
 for Marine Corps-specific munitions. This ensures the integrity of the design and prevents unauthorized or unsafe modifications throughout the ammunition's lifecycle. Delivers the rigorous systems engineering
 analysis and testing required to guarantee the safety and reliability of our ammunition, directly preventing malfunctions that could endanger Marines in training or combat. Leveraging the existing infrastructure
 and expertise at the NSWCs prevents the Marine Corps from having to create a costly and duplicative organic capability, ensuring fiscal responsibility while maintaining technical superiority.

 The Expeditionary Systems Engineering Division (ESED) budget funds the Marine Corps' designated In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) for conventional ground ammunition. This budget provides critical
 engineering expertise to guarantee the quality and safety of ammunition for the warfighter. The ISEA's primary function is to serve as the Marine Corps' technical authority during the most important events


